{{Infobox language family |name=Hatam–Mansim |altname=Hatam–Moi Brai |region=Eastern [[Bird's Head]], Indonesian Papua |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[West Papuan]] |fam2=(extended) East Bird's Head |child1=[[Hattam language|Hatam]] |child2=[[Mansim language|Mansim (Borai)]] |glotto=hata1242 |glottorefname=Hatam–Mansim }}
'''Hatam–Mansim''' is a small language family of New Guinea, consisting of two languages: *[[Hattam language|Hatam]] *[[Mansim language|Mansim (Borai)]]
Ross (2005) tentatively classified Hatam as a branch of the [[West Papuan languages|West Papuan]] family, based on similarities in pronouns (he did not consider Mansim), but ''Glottolog'' continues to list Hatam–Mansim as an independent family.<ref name=Glottolog/> Following Reesink (2002), ''Glottolog'' lists Mansim as a language distinct from Hattam: "comparisons of old wordlists (e.g. von der Gabelentz & Meyer 1882) readily confirm this difference."<ref>Hammarström (2015) Ethnologue 16/17/18th editions: a comprehensive review: online appendices</ref>
